bo?.text:
TUTORIAL ON HOW TO ADD CHARACTERS
---------------------------------------------------------------

(Updated as of b14.0_08a [v14.0])

So, you want to add characters... very cool...

Anyways, this comment will poorly teach you how to do it!

Stuff changes between updates, so this'll hopefully* be updated if anything changes to how characters are handled.

So, let's get started!

1. Character Initialization
    The "technical" stuff. There is a custom block next to this comment where you can input values listed below.
    First, "id". This ones simple, put the characters name into the spot. It should preferably be all lowercase, but spaces are NOT allowed, and should be ignored or substituted with something else, like an underscore. Character IDs are used for the game to determine what character you are using.
    Second, "name". This one is sorta like the last one, but you don't have to have everything be lowercase and don't have to have spaces be replaced with underscores or whatever. This goes in the "add [] to [Character List]" block instead of the custom block. Once you have put the name in the block, run it. If you are adding multiple characters, make sure the blocks are run in the right order.
    Third, "health". This one is simple, just put the health value you want for the character. The highest used by one of my characters is 280, being Heavy. The lowest one of my characters uses is 150, being used by Freddy, Bonnie, Foxy, and Chica (if you are ignoring Sheldon Cooper and Epic Mario).
    Fourth, "size". Here is where you set the size that is set to the sprite when your character is chosen. If you leave this blank, it will default to 80.
    Fifth, "y". Here is where you set the y position that is set to the sprite when your character is chosen. If you leave this blank, it will default to 0.
    Sixth, "vanilla?". Leave this blank. Simple, really? Characters I add have something there, but you are not me, therefore you do not have to input anything.
    Seventh, "# of frames". Simple, put the amount of costumes your character has, BUT, it needs to be subtracted by 1. So, if your character has 10 frames of animation, put 9. If your character ISN'T animated (or has 1 costume), put 0.
    Now, you can attach the custom block into the IF block attached to the 'load_game.modded' broadcast

2. Character Icon
    You'll need to add a costume to the "charaIcons" sprite. Make sure the costume name is the same as the character's ID. The costume needs to be 70x70. This should be all you need to worry about regarding the character icon.

3. Costumes.
    This is pretty straight forward. If your character is animated, then add all the frames of animation (make sure they are in the right order). If they aren't animated, then just add the single image. Make sure you set your character's costumes to your character's ID with "//" appended to it, i.e. freddy//, or nightmare_bonnie//, along with the frame number in which it appears. If you are confused, you can look at my other characters as an example

4. Attacks
    You'll have to go to "attackButtons" sprite. From there, you'll need to find the comment attached to 3 list blocks. You have to put the names of attacks into the custom block to determine the attacks for the character. You can look in the "attacksNamespace" list for the available attacks.

5. Category (Optional)
    You gotta set the dude's category now! This is used for the category feature in the character selection screen. By default, your character should show in the 'all' and 'modded' category. But, if you want your character to show in one of the other categories, then go to the category's list in the 'charaIcons' sprite and add your character's ID name into it (NOTE: You are able to put your character into multiple categories, not just one).

6. Test
    Now you gotta make sure your character works! Hit the 9 key, then hit the green flag. This should cause the game to reload everything, adding your character(s). The icon should appear, the character should have the right costume, health should be correct, attacks should be correct, blah blah blah. If something is incorrect, look back through the tutorial and see if you did something wrong.
